As of now, when a user edits a *JIRA* issue or closes it, the *Date Time Picker* is showing the server date. After saving and editing it again, the values entered will reflect the correct timezone value from the user's side.

Now this is of course an expected behavior since the date time picker format will follow the server date. The argument that we have here is that imagine if the instance has users from all over the world, different time zones. What will happen if the *Date Time Picker* format is overridden every time from the user's side due to different time zones? This will cause inaccuracy in terms of data.

HOWEVER, (here comes the interesting part) what if the *Date Time Picker* is seen as the right format from the user's perspective of time zone BUT from the server side, it still is standardized? This can be very helpful for users who rely on this for time tracking certain issues. This means that *JIRA* is dynamic and smart to detect the time zone from the *User Profile* directly & show the right format to the user but at the same time still retains the server time zone.

